<br>
Children are like that. A parent instills in a child right and wrong. They instill in thier child the ability to make the right decisions and to think through the action before making a decision.<br>
<br>
Nature vs Nurture... A parent nurtures thier child so they can deal with the things around them. As a child grows a parents role and responsibilites becomes even harder. You do not send a 2 year old to the store along because they are not ready for that yet, and you do not send a 14 year old to a party if they are not ready for it yet. Every step a child takes, every rite of passage has to come with guidance from thier parents.<br>
<br>
No, you do not have to follow your kid 24/7 if you have properly instilled the knowledge in them to be able to handle the situations that may arise. If you fulfill your role as a parents you send your child out with the confidence that they will make the right decisions. This does not mean telling them &quot;drugs are bad so don't do them&quot; it means teaching them why drugs are wrong, what happens to people using them, about peer pressure, about how to handle a situation if it comes up. It also means you communicate to them that you trust them and that is why they are allowed the privledge of going out. If you honestly fullfiled your responsibility as a parent then your child will make the right decisions.<br>
<br>
The bond and relationship you establish with your child has to start at the very beginning. It has to be full involvement from the very start of thier lives. This is not an over the night process, it is a foundation for things later on.<br>
<br>
The boy in this school shooting had been failing school. An involved parent would of known this and taken the steps to improve his grades before it reached the point of him no longer being in school. If they had fullfilled thier role, he would of passed that 2nd chance exam. His whole life would of been different. Yes it was his decision to kill others. Yes it was his parents fault that he came to that decision. <p>Crackanna Breeze<BR>
