<br>
I think making blanket statements like &quot;school shootings are caused by bad parenting,&quot; or &quot;these kids all need a good whooping,&quot; is extremely nearsighted. I don't think there is any one answer to the problem, and I do tend to think the whole issue of violence in schools is more complicated than it's being portrayed here. Further, blaming all parents on the actions of their teenaged children leads to a pattern of excuses. If teenagers, who are sometimes more adult than some adults, can commit crimes and have the guilt placed on their parents, then can't we say the same for all criminals? I wouldn't. Is crime always the product of bad parenting? Of course not. It would be naive to believe that there aren't a variety of forces at work which lead to criminal behavior. I believe the same can be said for teenagers. And if we really really want to finger point, maybe we should take a look at the place where kids spend 8 hours out of ever day, and the people they spend those eight hours with. Shouldn't the fact that these kids choose to shoot up their SCHOOL say anything about what could have possibly gone wrong with them?<br>
<br>
I don't think parent's should be absolved of all responsibility for their teenage children's actions, but placing total blame on them is too convenient, and really just seems like a way to bypass the issue by saying &quot;well, this is something that happens to BAD parents. To other people. I'm a good parent, so I don't have to worry,&quot; when in fact, that is the exact attitude that allows parents to continue turning a blind eye to the real issues in their children's lives. Don't assume. Your kid could be the next school shooter, or the next victim, no one is magically immune by merit of their l337 childraising skillz. The world just isn't that perfect.<br>
<br>
Trabious<br>
