Stylee <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/ubulvaihammersson.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BulvaiHammersson</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(5/5/02 11:38:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=301.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OT- Another School Shooting</span><hr size=1> Nature vs Nurture. I figured someone would eventually bring this up.<br>
<br>
Let's look at it, maybe use some words with slightly different connotations.<br>
<br>
You are, we all are, the sum of our genetics and experiences. That's it. There's nothing else there. It's either there at birth, or happens later.<br>
<br>
Hmm, Nature = genetics. Nurture = experiences.<br>
<br>
So basically, we are the sum of Nature plus Nurture.<br>
<br>
Well, Nature/genetics is pretty much locked at birth. Your genes will stay the same, excepting certain rare mutative influences such as carcinogens or radiation. <br>
<br>
Nurture/experience happens constantly, changes constantly.<br>
<br>
Well, as a parent, you are responsible, directly, for both.<br>
<br>
As a parent, excepting adoption or surrogate parents of course, you provide the genetic material. You and the other parent are DNA donors. Thus you are directly and irrefutably responsible for the &quot;nature&quot; part of the equation. <br>
<br>
We can get into discussions on &quot;born evil&quot; if you'd like, but I'd be really damned impressed if you can show empirically that someone was &quot;born bad&quot; and that their environment had zero influence on this.<br>
<br>
As a parent, you are directly responsible for the experience/nurture portion of the equation throughout the absolutely core-importance formative years prior to the child entering the education system. The values and behaviours that you instill as a parent in your toddler will stand them well or ill for the rest of their lives.<br>
<br>
The idea here is that you cannot build a great house on a crap foundation. Does a bad foundation ensure a bad house? No, but it certainly makes it a probability. The converse is equally true, as a good foundation does not guarantee a good house, though it does help.<br>
<br>
Once the child is out of the formative years, you are still the primary person responsible for their nurture and socialization, though you may share active duties with the rest of the folk the child comes into contact with. Still, all in all, you are the single most respected opinion in the child's life. The average child, while listening to their friends heavily, will admit that their parents are still an enormous influence on their lives, regardless of age.<br>
<br>
As time goes on, a parent has declining influence on the child's lifestyle choices, admittedly. This does not however absolve said parent of blame or responsibility though, as the parent still has the obligation to do everything they can to insure that the child/teen is not getting into trouble, preventable or not. At this stag in the child's existence, they are making more of their own choices and referencing your opinion less.<br>
<br>
The important point here is that, if you done your job laying the proper foundation, the child will have so much better an ability to make proper choices. Instill good values and morals, and teach the child to think through things reasonably, and you've done well to discharge your obligations as a parent. Teach no values or negative values, ignore morals, and fail to teach reasonable decision making and you have failed to adequately discharge your responsibilities.<br>
<br>
Look at yourself objectively, distance yourself from some of the emotions surrounding this, and give your parents some thought. They are more responsible for who and what you are than you might give them credit for.<br>
<br>
And, again, in the end of the argument, your parents inflicted you upon the world. It's their fault =) <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
