<br>
When I see parents dealing with kids in a mall, I hear &quot;Billy, don't do that.. Billy, please stop... Billy, don't touch that... Billy, put that down.... Billy, come here... Billy, please come here... Billy, don't hit that little girl... Billy... Billy.. &quot;  Grrrr.<br>
<br>
I grind my teeth at stuff like that.  Give ME that little dipsh*t Billy for about 10 minutes.  The moment he hears his name called by his parents, trust me.. some cold sh*t will run down his spine as he freezes and waits for his parents' next command.  He WILL listen and he WILL obey.  That's what kids should do.  They must first learn how to behave before they learn how to misbehave.<br>
<br>
Then I'll take the parents aside and teach THEM how to &quot;negatively motivate&quot; when it is appropriate.  There's nothing wrong with a beating now and then, as long as it's justified.  And whoa be the fuking parent who tells ME that they disapprove of my hitting the child.  I LOVE getting those mutterances under their breath.... And they think that my hearing ain't perfect.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey pal.. shut yer fuking piehole.. if someone gave YOU a little beating now and again when YOU were young, then you'd have learned by now to mind your own damned business.&quot;  That usually shuts them up pretty good.  Usually, I'm not mean to strangers.. but I give a great &quot;hairy eyeball&quot; when it is warranted.  That usually conveys enough 'do not mess with me' meaning to leave any verbal abuse out of the picture.<br>
<br>
You say that you &quot;grew up fine&quot;.  I'm sure you did.  And I'm sure many of us did.  I grew up fine, too.  But I remember more than a few moments in my life when I swore to God that &quot;I'd never do THAT again!&quot;.  Here's an example from my youth.  As a young teen, I once started a forest fire.  I'm not lying.   It was a blaze about 15 or 20 feet high, encompassing about half an acre.  It was burning full force for at least 10 min before the firemen just barely got it under control.  All because me and my friends were messing with fireworks one dry July afternoon.<br>
<br>
Well... let me tell you.  I caught such a beating that night from my mother.  She was a large-framed Italian woman - so naturally her weapon of choice was &quot;the big wooden spoon&quot; (+2 dam to 1H blunt weapon skill, I think) used to make all those infamous pasta sauces.  Not the little one she used to taste test, but the big one.  The.  Big.  One.  The one that she used when she wanted to kill Volkswagons.<br>
<br>
She broke it over... my... head.  Without even working up a sweat, she broke it over my head.  Try and break a wooden ANYTHING over your head.  Trust me.. it hurt so much my sister was even crying.  I saw spots for an hour.<br>
<br>
Moral to the story: I never - NEVER - messed with fireworks again.  Ever.  I still get headaches when I watch fireworks at the pier.<br>
<br>
Somethings, you take with you to your grave because your parents taught you to do things right.  It was their job and they did it well.<br>
